The story description is "Four rooms. Four seasons. One eternal loop."

Part 1 - The World

Chapter 1 - Winter

Winter is a room. "Bare branches scratch against a pale sky. Snow blankets everything in heavy silence, muffling your footsteps.[paragraph break]A path leads south toward warmth, or north into falling leaves."

Some bare branches are scenery in Winter. The description is "Dark and skeletal against the white sky, creaking softly in the wind."
Understand "branch" and "tree" and "trees" as the bare branches.

The snow is scenery in Winter. The description is "Pristine and endless, glittering faintly where light touches it."

Chapter 2 - Spring

Spring is south of Winter. "Crocuses push through thawing earth. A breeze carries the scent of wet soil and new blossoms. Birdsong threads through the canopy above.[paragraph break]The path continues south toward brighter light, or north toward the cold."

Some crocuses are scenery in Spring. The description is "Purple and white, fragile but stubborn — the first to arrive, every year."
Understand "crocus" and "flowers" and "flower" and "blossoms" and "blossom" as the crocuses.

The birdsong is scenery in Spring. The description is "You can[apostrophe]t see the birds, but their song is everywhere — layered and intricate, as though the whole canopy were singing."
Understand "birds" and "bird" and "song" and "canopy" as the birdsong.

Chapter 3 - Summer

Summer is south of Spring. "Sunlight pours through a cathedral of green leaves. The air hums with warmth and the drowsy buzz of insects. Tall grass ripples in slow waves.[paragraph break]South, the light turns golden. North, it softens."

The tall grass is scenery in Summer. The description is "It sways at waist height, seed-heavy and golden at the tips."
Understand "grass" and "meadow" and "seeds" as the tall grass.

The sunlight is scenery in Summer. The description is "It falls in bright columns through the leaf canopy, thick and almost tangible."
Understand "sun" and "light" and "leaves" as the sunlight.

Chapter 4 - Fall

Fall is south of Summer. South of Fall is Winter. "Leaves drift in spirals of amber and crimson. The light is golden and low, casting long shadows through thinning trees.[paragraph break]The path continues south toward the cold, or north toward the warmth."

The falling leaves are scenery in Fall. The description is "They spin slowly as they descend — oak, maple, birch — each one catching the light before it settles."
Understand "leaf" as the falling leaves.

